  <section>
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <FaqAccordion>
      <FaqItem question="Are coffee makers with grinder and K-Cup combo systems worth it?">
        <p>Yes for mixed households that genuinely use both bean and pod modes. They are less worth it when your routine is almost all pods or almost all bean brewing.</p>
      </FaqItem>
      <FaqItem question="Can one machine really handle beans, ground coffee, and K-Cups well?">
        <p>The better hybrids can, but performance is usually strongest in one primary mode. Most still involve trade-offs between grinder quality, speed, and cleaning complexity.</p>
      </FaqItem>
      <FaqItem question="Is a burr grinder necessary in a hybrid machine?">
        <p>Not strictly, but burr grinders improve flavor clarity and consistency. If cup quality is your top goal, burr models are worth the higher price.</p>
      </FaqItem>
      <FaqItem question="How often should I deep-clean these combo systems to avoid clogs?">
        <p>Do a quick rinse daily, targeted chute and pod-path cleaning weekly, and full descale/deep-clean monthly. Hard-water homes often need descaling every 2-3 weeks.</p>
      </FaqItem>
      <FaqItem question="What is a realistic brew time from whole beans to one cup?">
        <p>Most hybrid one-cup models take around 4-6 minutes from whole beans. Carafe-focused machines usually need 8-10 minutes for a full batch.</p>
      </FaqItem>
    </FaqAccordion>
